### A Data Snapshot to Digest
As of this year, food recalls have reached 302, with 84 of those being Class I recalls - the most serious due to potential for severe health consequences. Topping the offenders' list is Moonlight Packing Corporation, with a record of 11 Class I recalls, all tied to their Grade F performance score.

### April's Highlight Recalls
Most recently, April 8th saw a flurry of recalls. For instance, Lone Star Dairy Products flagged their Spray Dried Dairy Powder for Salmonella contamination, a clear Class I recall. Meanwhile, JFE Franchising faced a Class II recall for dumplings containing glass shards. Other recalls included undeclared milk allergens and compromised packaging integrity – issues spanning multiple brands.

### Trends and Insights
April's recalls prominently feature allergens and foreign objects, reflecting industry-wide lapses in quality control. Repeat offenders, such as Moonlight Packing Corporation and Albertsons Companies LLC, continue to dominate the recall narrative. Conversely, smaller players like Pocas International Corp. have made their debut into April's lineup with packaging concerns across several products.

### The Verdict
Consumers must remain vigilant as both established and new brands contribute to an ever-growing list of recalls. Abruptly labeled products and inconsistent quality assurance protocols only amplify the risks faced by the consumer base.

### Brands to Watch
Notable brands flagged this month include:
- Moonlight Packing Corporation
- Albertsons Companies LLC
- Pocas International Corp.
- JFE Franchising Inc.

These names reflect an ongoing need for scrutiny, especially among repeat offenders.
